		<div class="entry" id="post-7806">

			<h2 class="title"><a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/how-to-turn-leftover-chicken-into-a-tasty-soup.html">How To Turn Leftover Chicken Into A Tasty Soup</a></h2>
		
			<span class="date">March 12, 2012 | By Adam Roberts | <a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/how-to-turn-leftover-chicken-into-a-tasty-soup.html#comments">0 Comments</a></span>
			
			<div class="share-main">
			<ul>
				<li class="fb-share"><iframe id="fbshare" src="http://www.facebook.com/plugins/like.php?href=http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/how-to-turn-leftover-chicken-into-a-tasty-soup.html&amp;layout=button_count&amp;show_faces=false&amp;width=90&amp;action=like&amp;colorscheme=light" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" allowTransparency="true" style="border:none; overflow:hidden; width:90px; "></iframe></li>
				<li class="tm-share"><a href="http://twitter.com/share" class="twitter-share-button" data-text="How To Turn Leftover Chicken Into A Tasty Soup" data-url="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/how-to-turn-leftover-chicken-into-a-tasty-soup.html" data-count="horizontal" data-via="amateurgourmet"></a></li>
			</ul>
			</div><div class="clearer"></div>
			
			<p><a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/amateurgourmet/6976741847/" title="leftoverchickensoup1 by The Amateur Gourmet, on Flickr"><img src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7203/6976741847_84712e2ce5_o.jpg" width="605" height="404" alt="leftoverchickensoup1"/></a></p>
<p>One benefit of making a complicated, classic dish like <a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/bouillabaisse-a-french-seafood-odyssey-at-home.html">bouillabaisse</a>, as I did last week, is that the process of making it becomes its own version of cooking school. You follow the steps but as you do so, you learn things. For example: making a fumet (or fish stock) may be labor-intensive but your efforts pay off later when that highly flavored broth is poured in with the tomatoes and onions and fish and takes your bouillabaisse over the moon. Why couldn&#8217;t I apply a similar strategy with leftover chicken and leftover chicken carcasses? Last week, that&#8217;s precisely what I did.</p>
<p> <a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/how-to-turn-leftover-chicken-into-a-tasty-soup.html#more-7806" class="more-link">Continue Reading &raquo;</a></p>

		</div><!-- close entry -->

	
	
					
	

	

	
	
	
		<div class="entry" id="post-7789">

			<h2 class="title"><a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/the-salted-caramel-latte.html">The Salted Caramel Latte</a></h2>
		
			<span class="date">March 9, 2012 | By Adam Roberts | <a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/the-salted-caramel-latte.html#comments">0 Comments</a></span>
			
			<div class="share-main">
			<ul>
				<li class="fb-share"><iframe id="fbshare" src="http://www.facebook.com/plugins/like.php?href=http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/the-salted-caramel-latte.html&amp;layout=button_count&amp;show_faces=false&amp;width=90&amp;action=like&amp;colorscheme=light" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" allowTransparency="true" style="border:none; overflow:hidden; width:90px; "></iframe></li>
				<li class="tm-share"><a href="http://twitter.com/share" class="twitter-share-button" data-text="The Salted Caramel Latte" data-url="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/the-salted-caramel-latte.html" data-count="horizontal" data-via="amateurgourmet"></a></li>
			</ul>
			</div><div class="clearer"></div>
			
			<p><a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/amateurgourmet/6811041306/" title="saltedcaramellatte1 by The Amateur Gourmet, on Flickr"><img src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7186/6811041306_607800a85c_o.jpg" width="605" height="452" alt="saltedcaramellatte1"/></a></p>
<p>At the new bakery Short Cake, I encountered a drink that&#8217;s so absolutely brilliant it deserves fireworks or a parade but that&#8217;s simply presented without any fanfare or fuss. If it were a Starbucks, you&#8217;d see signs all over the place advertising the Salted Caramel Latte. As it stands, you sort of have to discover it for yourself&#8211;it&#8217;s there on the menu, below the mocha and the vanilla bean and across from Aunt Nancy&#8217;s Shakerato (named for Nancy Silverton, I imagine)&#8211;but it&#8217;s not highlighted or underlined in any way.</p>
<p> <a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/the-salted-caramel-latte.html#more-7789" class="more-link">Continue Reading &raquo;</a></p>

		</div><!-- close entry -->

	
	
					
	

	

	
	
	
		<div class="entry" id="post-7763">

			<h2 class="title"><a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/an-imaginative-feast-by-food-prodigy-andy-windak-mac-n-cheese-stuffed-ravioli-coq-au-vin-chilaquiles-a-roasted-feast-by-cookbook-hero-molly-stevens.html">An Imaginative Feast By Food Prodigy Andy Windak (Mac &#8216;n&#8217; Cheese Stuffed Ravioli! Coq au Vin Chilaquiles!) &#038; A Roasted Feast By Cookbook Hero Molly Stevens</a></h2>
		
			<span class="date">March 7, 2012 | By Adam Roberts | <a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/an-imaginative-feast-by-food-prodigy-andy-windak-mac-n-cheese-stuffed-ravioli-coq-au-vin-chilaquiles-a-roasted-feast-by-cookbook-hero-molly-stevens.html#comments">0 Comments</a></span>
			
			<div class="share-main">
			<ul>
				<li class="fb-share"><iframe id="fbshare" src="http://www.facebook.com/plugins/like.php?href=http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/an-imaginative-feast-by-food-prodigy-andy-windak-mac-n-cheese-stuffed-ravioli-coq-au-vin-chilaquiles-a-roasted-feast-by-cookbook-hero-molly-stevens.html&amp;layout=button_count&amp;show_faces=false&amp;width=90&amp;action=like&amp;colorscheme=light" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" allowTransparency="true" style="border:none; overflow:hidden; width:90px; "></iframe></li>
				<li class="tm-share"><a href="http://twitter.com/share" class="twitter-share-button" data-text="An Imaginative Feast By Food Prodigy Andy Windak (Mac &#8216;n&#8217; Cheese Stuffed Ravioli! Coq au Vin Chilaquiles!) &#038; A Roasted Feast By Cookbook Hero Molly Stevens" data-url="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/an-imaginative-feast-by-food-prodigy-andy-windak-mac-n-cheese-stuffed-ravioli-coq-au-vin-chilaquiles-a-roasted-feast-by-cookbook-hero-molly-stevens.html" data-count="horizontal" data-via="amateurgourmet"></a></li>
			</ul>
			</div><div class="clearer"></div>
			
			<p><a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/amateurgourmet/6962225747/" title="andyhimself by The Amateur Gourmet, on Flickr"><img src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7038/6962225747_7dc9bb5d98_o.jpg" width="605" height="403" alt="andyhimself"/></a></p>
<p>I don&#8217;t follow sports, but I know that there are these people called scouts who go around to minor league events and look for future stars to recruit to the majors. Well, I never considered myself much of a chef scout, but that all changed on Sunday when food blogger Andy Windak&#8211;of the food blog <a href="http://windattack.com/">The Wind Attack</a>&#8211;invited us over for dinner. I was wary of this 25 year-old who talked a big game the first few times that I met him (he said something about <a href="http://windattack.com/recipe/marinated-yucca-blossoms/">marinated yucca blossoms</a>) but what I didn&#8217;t realize was that he was the real deal: a self-taught, self-motivated prodigy who works wonders in the kitchen.</p>
<p> <a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/an-imaginative-feast-by-food-prodigy-andy-windak-mac-n-cheese-stuffed-ravioli-coq-au-vin-chilaquiles-a-roasted-feast-by-cookbook-hero-molly-stevens.html#more-7763" class="more-link">Continue Reading &raquo;</a></p>

		</div><!-- close entry -->

	
	
					
	

	

	
	
	
		<div class="entry" id="post-7754">

			<h2 class="title"><a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/lindsey-sheres-legendary-almond-tart.html">Lindsey Shere&#8217;s Legendary Almond Tart</a></h2>
		
			<span class="date">March 6, 2012 | By Adam Roberts | <a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/lindsey-sheres-legendary-almond-tart.html#comments">0 Comments</a></span>
			
			<div class="share-main">
			<ul>
				<li class="fb-share"><iframe id="fbshare" src="http://www.facebook.com/plugins/like.php?href=http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/lindsey-sheres-legendary-almond-tart.html&amp;layout=button_count&amp;show_faces=false&amp;width=90&amp;action=like&amp;colorscheme=light" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" allowTransparency="true" style="border:none; overflow:hidden; width:90px; "></iframe></li>
				<li class="tm-share"><a href="http://twitter.com/share" class="twitter-share-button" data-text="Lindsey Shere&#8217;s Legendary Almond Tart" data-url="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/lindsey-sheres-legendary-almond-tart.html" data-count="horizontal" data-via="amateurgourmet"></a></li>
			</ul>
			</div><div class="clearer"></div>
			
			<p><a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/amateurgourmet/6956559051/" title="almondtartslice by The Amateur Gourmet, on Flickr"><img src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7193/6956559051_e531ebab7a_o.jpg" width="605" height="404" alt="almondtartslice"/></a></p>
<p>I suppose I must really like a challenge because, on the night that I made the <a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/bouillabaisse-a-french-seafood-odyssey-at-home.html">bouillabaisse</a>, I also attempted a famously difficult dessert: Lindsey Shere&#8217;s Almond Tart.</p>
<p>Lindsey Shere, in case you don&#8217;t know, helped open <a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2007/04/my_dinner_at_ch.html">Chez Panisse</a> in 1971 and stayed there as pastry chef until 1998. I first heard about her famous almond tart on my trip to San Francisco in 2007; I think it was at a place called <a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2007/04/cesar_jojo.html">Jojo</a> in Oakland, with my friends Derrick and Melissa, that I first heard tell about it. The word &#8220;legendary&#8221; might&#8217;ve been applied. </p>
<p> <a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/lindsey-sheres-legendary-almond-tart.html#more-7754" class="more-link">Continue Reading &raquo;</a></p>

		</div><!-- close entry -->

	
	
					
	

	

	
	
		
		<div class="shortspost">
			<p><a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2012/03/a-dickensian-banner.html" class="shortstitle">A Dickensian Banner</a> &mdash; Did you know that I was in "Oliver" twice in my life? First as Oliver in my 5th grade production and then as Fagan in 7th grade. It wasn't until after college, though, that I read my first Dickens novel ("Bleak House," for the record) and became an instant fan. This month I said to <a href="http://lindygroening.com/">Lindy</a>, "What if we do a banner in the style of a Dickens illustration?" And being the talented person that she is, she came up with the banner you see above. I <a href="http://youtu.be/nNapDkz1urc">consider myself</a> lucky to have her.  </p>
		</div>
	
	
					
	

	

	
	


